author: Atama kita
title: Copy right detection.
content:
I need to point out how broken the copyright detection system is for live stream highlights. 
Hereâ€™s the situation: I perform original music live on TikTok. The audio is created in real-time by 
me on hardware instruments. The performance is streamed on TikTok, recorded by TikTok, and stored 
on TikTok.

Later, when I use the built-in tool to clip highlights from the exact same livestream that was 
already broadcast on TikTok, the app suddenly claims that the audio belongs to someone else. 

How does that make any sense? The platform saw the audio originate LIVE, in real-time, from me. 
It is literally the same video file from the same stream already stored on TikTokâ€™s own servers. 
There is no external upload. There is no third-party audio. There is no sample of someone elseâ€™s 
music. It is my performance from start to finish.

The fact that TikTok canâ€™t recognize audio that was created on TikTok, streamed on TikTok, and 
clipped on TikTok is incredibly frustrating. Artists shouldnâ€™t be punished by the platform for 
making original content. The system needs to link audio created in TikTok Live to audio used in 
TikTok highlights, instead of treating original work as someone elseâ€™s.
